player.seasonOutlook: Kuzma parlayed his best career season into a huge contract extension with the Wizards this offseason and returns as the primary frontcourt scoring option on the team. Kuzma is a consistent 20 PPG scorer, but on a talent-bereft Wizards squad he has 25 PPG upside. There is still a chance that Kuzma is dealt this season as the Wizards look to rebuild, and if he does move to a more talented squad then his scoring volume and fantasy output would likely decrease.

Giddey burst onto the scene in his sophomore campaign, pairing with Shai Gilgeous-Alexander to become the star backcourt for the Thunder. Giddey has been a regular triple-double threat since entering the league, but last season he upped his scoring to the mid-upper teens to become more of an offense impact player. He will be freshly 21 years old to start his Magical Third Year, and with his size, passing ability and the increasing level of talent around him Giddey has the opportunity to make another leap this season.

Mobley improved his production and efficiency across the board in his sophomore season, building on his All Rookie First Team inaugural season. He particularly improved his scoring efficiency, taking advantage of the additional space afforded by Donovan Mitchell and Darius Garland drawing opposing defenses and helping create good shots for their big man. Mobley increased to 16.2 PPG and 9.0 RPG last season, and has the potential to flirt with averages of 20 and 10 in this, his magical third campaign.

McCollum is a natural combo guard that would ideally be a third option on a contending team, but for the Pelicans he has been playing point guard as a second option behind Brandon Ingram with Zion Williamson largely injured. The added responsibility didn't translate to more volume, though, with McCollum notching his lowest scoring average since 2015-16 and his lowest field goal percentae since 2014-15. McCollum isn't a pure floor general, but in this role he is good for almost six assists per game. And if Williamson is healthy this season, it might cost McCollum a point or two of volume but would likely help him bounce-back as a shooter who could play off two other stars.

Sengun made major strides as a sophomore, becoming a full-time starter and averaging a strong 15.0 PPG, 9.4 RPG, 5.0 APG, 1.2 SPG and 0.9 BPG over his last 39 games of the season. Sengun is a new-age center on offense, in the mold of Nikola Jokic and Domantas Sabonis, that can act a hub to both score and create offense for teammates. In his third NBA season, he has the clear potential to average a double-double with upper-teens points and six-plus assists in play as well.

Kessler burst onto the scene with a surprising All Rookie First Team selection, based largely on his excellent defense. Kessler moved into the starting lineup for good in the second hal of the season, and in his last 34 games averaged 10.5 RPG and 2.9 BPG. On offense, he's a high-efficiency finisher who notched 11.9 PPG on 71.7 FG% during that same stretch. Kessler played for Team USA in the FIBA World Cup this offseason, raising his cache around the league, and he enters this season as a top-60 fantasy hoops prospect with upside.

It was long-rumored that Ayton would be traded, and those rumors came to fruition when he was part of a three-team deal between the Suns, Trail Blazers and Bucks. There's been a lot of criticism about Ayton's inconsistent play and lack of effort, especially during the playoffs, but his new role as a veteran leader on a young Trail Blazers team provides him an opportunity to rehabilitate his NBA career and exceed fantasy managers' expectations. With Kevin Durant, Devin Booker and Bradley Beal out of the picture, Ayton should have a high usage rate in the Rose City. Ayton averaged 18 PPG, 10 RPG and 0.8 BPG in 30.4 MPG last season and the Trail Blazers should rely on him more for scoring.

Holiday operated on higher volumes last season, turning in the second-highest scoring and assist numbers of his career as he filled in for the injured Khris Middleton as the second option on the Bucks. He paid for the added offensive volume with a decrease in efficiency (lowest field goal percentage since joining the Bucks) and a drop in defensive stats (fewest steals since rookie season, first season with fewer than 2.0 combined steals and blocks since 2015-16). Now in Boston by way of Portland (as a part of the Damian Lillard trade), Holiday's scoring could suffer but his numbers should be similar to last season in most other statistical categories.

Henderson joins the Trail Blazers as the heir apparent to Damian Lillard, and the future begins now with Lillard traded to Milwaukee. Henderson is an explosive scoring lead-guard, and would have received serious consideration for the number one overall draft pick in most seasons that don't include Victor Wembanyama. Henderson can get into the lane off the bounce and break down opposing defenses, either finishing in the paint or setting up teammates for open looks. He has a good chance to be among rookie leaders in points and assists, and is one of the frontrunners for Rookie of the Year as he enters the season.

VanVleet has established himself as a primary offensive weapon, averaging 19.8 PPG, 6.8 APG and 3.3 3PG in his last three seasons with the Raptors. This offseason he signed a max contract with the Rockets, and assumes the primary playmaking role on a young, talented roster with upside at every position. VanVleet could be in for a larger than expected role this season as well, with incumbent starter Kevin Porter Jr. mired in legal issues that seem likely to affect his availability.

Reaves burst onto the scene in his sophomore campaign, eventually earning the full-time starting job on the wing as a scorer and secondary playmaker. Reaves averaged 19.8 PPG, 5.8 APG, 3.7 RPG and 1.5 3PG in the last 13 games of the season, then averaged another 16.9 PPG, 4.6 APG, 4.4 RPG and 2.4 3PG in 16 postseason contests. Reaves played for the US National Team in the FIBA World Cup, further establishing himself as a rising star in the league, and his numbers should improve this season as he settles in to his new, key role on the Lakers.

Turner improved dramatically in his eighth NBA season, increasing his scoring average by more than five points to a career-best 18.0 PPG on a career best 54.8 FG%. Turner was the primary big man for the Pacers at both ends last season after Domantas Sabonis was traded during the previous campaign, and he showed that he still had offensive upside as he approached his athletic peak at age 27. Turner also remains one of the best shotblockers in the NBA, averaging 2.3 BPG last season and 2.6 BPG in the last five seasons.

Allen's volume dipped slightly across the board last season in the followup to his All Star 2021-22 campaign, but still averaged fractional rebounds short of a double-double on excellent field goal percentage with two combined blocks and steals per game. Allen is an energy defender and a pure finisher on offense, and his ability to athletically power into putbacks and dunks around the rim is invaluable on a team like the Cavaliers with multiple elite perimeter creators. Still only 25 years old, Allen has the potential to improve as he and frontcourt-mate Evan Mobley continue to develop into one of the best frontlines in the NBA.

Williams had an excellent first season, earning All Rookie First Team honors and finishing runner up to Paolo Banchero for Rookie of the Year. Williams was consistently able to use his size to his advantage on the wing, on both offense and defense, setting up high-percentage shots (52.1 FG%) at one end and disrputing his opponents (1.4 SPG, 0.5 BPG) at the other. He should be expected to improve as a sophomore, and has a top-75 fantasy basketball grade entering the season.

Middleton spent last season trying to recover and return from knee injuries, and the result was a partial season with only 33 games played, 19 starts and 24.3 MPG. His scoring volume and efficiency were both among the lowest in his career, and he had another knee procedure immediately after the season. Even so, the Bucks signed him to a two-year extension this offseason, indicating some level of confidence in his ability to recover. But with Damian Lillard now on the team, Middleton's volume will be more capped as the third option on the team.

Poeltl was traded back to the Raptors last season after spending the previous four years with the Spurs. Poeltl is a solid double-double threat on a nightly basis on excellent efficiency, and also can block a shot or two per game. Poeltl signed a four-year contract extension to remain the Raptors starting center for the foreseeable future, giving them a more traditional lineup with Pascal Siakam moving back to power forward. Poeltl is a high-floor/moderate ceiling player, a top-75 prospect in fantasy basketball that provides value in the middle-late portions of drafts.

George missed 26 games last season, and in his campaigns with the Clippers has averaged only 47.3 games played. Availability is George's biggest issue, because otherwise he continues to produce across-the-board with averages of 23.2 PPG, 6.3 RPG, 4.9 APG, 3.1 3PG and 1.5 SPG during his four seasons with the Clippers. If health permits, George is a top-25 fantasy hoops prospect, but his history makes him a risky pick near the top of fantasy drafts.

Russell was traded from the Timberwolves to the Lakers in the middle of the season, and statistically there wasn't much difference in his performance. At this point in his career, Russell's game, strengths and weaknesses are well-known. He's a scoring lead guard that can knock down the 3-pointer and put points on the board in a hurry when he's hot, but he can also fade into the background or be an off-ball decody for large stretches as well. His output could go down slightly this season when the other Lakers are healthy, because Austin Reaves gives the Lakers three plus scorers in addition to Russell and, of course, LeBron James is the primary playmaker on the team, but if the team continues to have injury issues he could also have to help carry them for extended periods in the season.

Green upped his scoring volume by almost five points per game as a sophomore, up to 22.1 PPG and 2.5 3PG. Green has the upside to turn in a similar step forward in his third season, with the combo of size, athleticism, shooting ability and aggressive mindset to eventually move his scoring average into the upper-20s and challeng for the league lead. How far he moves up that scoring continuum this season could be impacted by playing with the best lead guard of his career in Fred VanVleet, but also could be hampered with the array of talented young players on the Rockets that could require touches.

Vassell has developed steadily since being taken by the Spurs with the No. 11 pick in the 2020 NBA draft, from 5.5 PPG, 2.8 RPG and 0.8 3PG as a rookie up to 18.5 PPG, 3.9 RPG, 3.6 APG and 2.7 3PG last season. The Spurs signed him to a $146 million contract extension this summer, solidifying his status as their wing of the future. The biggest concern with Vassell is health, coming off a season in which he missed 44 games due to injury. He is expected to be healthy to start the season, and if he stays that way he could be in for a top-100 fantasy campaign.

Johnson has increase his scoring volume at the cost of diminished scoring efficiency in each of his first four NBA seasons, peaking with the 22.0 PPG on 45.2 FG% he generated last season. Johnson has a solid all-around game, with two-year averages of 5.6 RPG, 2.5 APG, 2.1 3PG and 0.8 SPG to give himself a solid top-75 fantasy basketball prospect with upside moving into his age 24 season.

Holmgren missed his entire first season in the pros due to injury, but enters his official rookie season healthy and in form. Holmgren played in the Las Vegas Summer League and teased his upside as an elite shotblocker on defense and a versatile scoring threat at the other. Holmgren will always be slim, but he has put on some muscle since being drafted that will serve him well at this level. He is the early favorite to lead this year's rookie class in shotblocking and is among the top non-Victor-Wembanyama favorites for Rookie of the Year.

Westbrook moved from one locker room in the Crypto.com center to another last season, playing his first 52 games with the Lakers and last 21 with the Clippers. Though Lakers fans treated him as a problem while the Clippers found him a solution, Westbrook's numbers were eerily similar across both franchises. At this point, in his 16th season, Westbrook is who he is. He is still a plus scorer and distibutor that crashes th boards well for a guard, and he will turn in more than one 3-pointer and steal per game. He appears set to start for the Clippers again, so he should continue to get around the 30 MPG required to produce those numbers.

Jones moved into the starting point guard role for the Spurs last season and effectively doubled his minutes from the previous seasonwhich also effectively doubled his production. While not the greatest shooter, Jones proved he could be a low-mid teens scorer with plus contributions in assists, rebounds and steals while still knocking down almost a 3-pointer per game. Jones signed an extension with the Spurs this offseason and projects to start again, and if so his minutes and role could increase now that he has a season of starting under his belt. If he has spent the offseason working on his jumper and can improve on his 28.5 3P% from last season, he has the upside to become an impact fantasy hoops producer this season.

Wagner followed up a strong rookie season with an even better sophomore campaign, increasing his scoring average, assists, 3-pointers made and field goal percentage to become an impact fantasy basketball producer. Wagner paired with Paolo Banchero to give the Magic one of the best young forward tandems in the league, both primary scorers and secondary facilitators. Wagner also has  averages a steal per game and a handful of boards, giving him solid defensive categories to supplement his offensive production.

Herro moved into the starting lineup for the Heat last season, continuinhg the progression from sixth man to impact player on a Heat team where star Jimmy Butler deals with chronic knee issues. Herro averaged over 20 PPG for the second straight season and set new career bests with 5.4 RPG, 4.2 APG, 3.0 3PG and 0.8 SPG. He also led the NBA with a 93.4 FT%, though his volume is too low (2.7 FTA) to make a big difference to fantasy hoops squads. WIth the end of the Damian Lillard trade rumors, Herro could be in for a bigger season with the Heat as he tries to carry more of the load and take pressure off the veterans.

Claxton stepped into the full-time starting center role for the Nets last season, and his per-minute averages translated almost perfectly in his increase to almost 30 MPG. His rebounding and blocked shot rates, as well as his field goal percentage all improved, rsulting in an NBA-leading 70.5 FG% and the third most blocks in the league at 2.5 BPG. Claxton's offensive upside is limited as a pure finisher that doesn't create his own shot nor have much jumper, but he is a nightly double-double threat with strong defensive production.

Murray used his excellent 3-point shooting stroke to score his way to a slot on the All-Rookie First Team. He knocked down 41.1% from behind the arc while making 2.6 3PG to supplement his low teens scoring, a handful of rebounds and just over a block-and-steal per game. As a rookie, Murray was almost purely a spot-up shooter, but he has more offensive game and it wouldn't be surprising if he integrates more into the offense as a sophomore to move further up the fantasy hoops top-100 as the season progresses.

Capella thrives as the finisher in the pick-and-roll game, so it's not surprising that he set a new career-best field goal percentage mark of 65.3% in his first season playing with two point guards in Trae Young and Dejounte Murray. Capela's defensive numbers were solid but down, with his 11.0 RPG and 1.2 BPG representing his lowest averages in the last five and six seasons, respectively.

The Timberwolves traded for Gobert in a blockbuster deal  before last season, banking on the experiment of starting two starting centers. The experiment did not work in Year 1, with Gobert turning in near-career-lows in scoring, rebounds and blocked shots for his new team even with Karl-Anthony Towns missing more than half the season injured. Gobert will look to bounce back this season, but it isn't clear there is enough production available for both Gobert and Towns to be maximized.

Harris has become a forgotten man in the 76ers offense, descending to the fourth option behind three other volume scorers. He is coming off his lowest scoring average since 2015-16, three teams before joining the 76ers. Harris has proven he can score 20 PPG on a nightly basis, but with his usage he is currently more like 15 PPG. The one wild card in Harris' value is James Harden, and whether he plays for the 76ers this season. If he is traded and another volume scorer doesn't come back, Harris could resume his usual third option role that allowed him to average 18.7 PPG in his first three full seasons with the 76ers.

Morant continued to progress on the court last season, setting new career bests with 8.1 APG and 5.9 RPG to go with his elite scoring numbers. Unfortunately, his game was overshadowed in the second half of the season by off-court situations that resulted in an eight-game suspension last season and will result in a 25-game suspension to begin this campaign. Morant has averaged only 59 games played in the last two seasons, and will play 57 or less this season as well, making availability an issue. When he returns, though, Morant is still growing and has a strong chance to improve his per-game numbers again in his age 24 season.

Wiggins turned in almost the exact same statistical effort last season as he had in his All Star campaign from 2021-22, but in about half as many games. Wiggins was limited to only 37 games last season by a combination of injury and personal issues, but it should be noted that before last season Wiggins had only missed 10 or more games once in his nine year career. If he returns to his typical durability this season, Wiggins remains a solid all-around player that can contribute positively with averages in the upper teens of scoring, more than two 3-pointers, a handful of rebounds and about two combined steals/blocks per game.

Simons showed two seasons ago when Damian Lillard was injured that he could step into a starting lead guard role, and last season he demonstrated his readiness to produce strong scoring volume even playing off Lillard. Simons scored 21.1 PPG with 3.4 3PG, and has upside to increase both of those numbers this season if Lillard is indeed traded. Simons is a pure shooter, and that would pair well with the penetrate-and-kick game of incoming point guard Scoot Henderson.

Valanciunas has averaged a double-double in four straight seasons, and did so again last season despite only playing 24.9 MPG. Valanciunas is a traditional center with great size, but in today's NBA the Pelicans have found it beneficial to play more small ball with multiple power forwards at times. Valanciunas could benefit if Zion Williamson plays more, because his size on defense helps make up for Zion's shorter stature. Either way, Valanciunas' per minute production is pretty established at this point in his career, it's just a question of how much he will be on the court.

Paul is entering his 19th NBA season at 38 years old, and for the second year in a row he is coming off the worst scoring season of his career. In addition, Paul was traded this offseason from a primary offensive role with the Phoenix Suns to a complementary role with the Golden State Warriors. It isn't clear whether Paul will start or come off the bench for the Warriors, but either way his minutes and opportunities to produce should fall significantly on a team with so many other scoring and playmaking options.

Clarkson earned a starting spot last season on the Jazz and parlayed it into a career campaign. He produced more than 20 PPG, four APG and four RPG, new career marks in all three categories, and enters this season as the team's lead guard and main playmaker. Clarkson is excellent from downtown, averaging 2.7 3PG in the past three seasons. After making his career as a sixth man, Clarkson's production as a starter moves him into the top-100 of fantasy hoops rankings with upside to move up.

Collins joins the Jazz this season after spending his first six seasons next to Trae Young on the Atlanta Hawks. Collins' production in Atlanta peaked at 21.6 PPG and 10.1 RPG in 2019-20, but his numbers have decreased across the board since as the Hawks relied more heavily on their backcourt. Like Lauri Markkanen last season, Collins has untapped potential that the Jazz may make use of by giving him a higher usage role. He and Markkanen are both combo forwards, so both should be able to play on the court at the same time. The tradeoff is that Collins won't have a playmaker of Young's caliber to set him up in Utah, but he should have the opportunity to show whether he is capable of consistently getting his own looks.

Anunoby has consistently been one of the best, highest-scoring 3-and-D wings in the NBA. In the last three seasons, he has averaged 16.6 PPG, 2.3 3PG and 1.6 SPG with solid supplementary numbers as well. The biggest risk with Anunoby, from a fantasy hoops perspective, is his injury history. He played 67 games last season, but in his previous three has only averaged 52.7 games per season.

Johnson was traded to the Nets last season, and in 25 games with Brooklyn he showed he could be more aggressive as a scorer than he had shown in his time with the Suns. Johnson made his name as a 3-point marksman, shooting 42% from behind the arc on about six attempts per game in his last season-plus with the Sun. He maintained similar 3-point volume with the Nets, but wasnt getting as many open looks set up by Devin Booker and Chris Paul, so his 3-point percentage dropped to a still respectable 37%. After signing a big extension with the Nets this off-season, he projects to a high-teens scorer with a handful of boards and strong 3-point shooting.

Portis has settled in as one of the best sixth man centers in the NBA, averaging almost a double-double with 14.4 PPG and 9.4 RPG in his last two seasons in 27.1 MPG. Portis still plays behind Brook Lopez, but has started about half of the games the last two seasons when Lopez or Giannis Antetokounmpo have been injured. Portis's star rose this offseason when he played for Team USA at the FIBA World Cup, but with Lopez re-signing, Portis should maintain a similar role for the Bucks this season.

Washington is coming off his best season as a scorer, having set career marks with 15.7 PPG and 2.0 3PG. On the flip side, his higher usage resulted in lower efficiency (career-lows 44.4 FG% and 34.8 3P%) and less energy on defense (career-lows 4.9 RPG and 0.9 SPG). Washington's scoring opportunities could take a hit this season with newly returned Miles Bridges and second overall pick Brandon Miller joining he and Gordon Hayward as scoring forwards, but if so his efficiency and defensive stats could bounce back.

Rozier is coming off a strong season in which he set new career-highs of 21.1 PPG and 5.1 APG, but it should be noted that starting point guard LaMelo Ball missed 46 games due to injury. With Ball healthy, as well as the additions of scorers like second overall pick Brandon Miller and the reinstated Miles Bridges, there could be fewer offensive opportunities for Rozier this season. Nevertheless, during his four seasons in Charlotte he has proven himself to reliable producer that also knocks down almost three treys and grabs more than a steal per game as well.

Lopez bounced back with 78 games played last season after managing only 13 the year before and turned in his best statistical season since 2016-17. His 15.9 PPG and 6.7 RPG both represented bests in a Bucks uniform, and his 2.5 BPG were a career high. Lopez re-signed with the Bucks this offseason, and should reprise his role as one of the best 3-and-D big men in the NBA.

Hield faced trade rumors all season, but remained with the Pacers and turned in his typical season: he averaged in the mid-upper teens scoring, between three and four treys, turned in a handful of rebounds and around a steal, and played in just about every game. Hield has not missed more than two games in any season of his career, and that consistent durability in addition to his excellent shooting keeps him a viable fantasy hoops starter on a year-in/year-out basis.

Beal was one of the leading scorers in the NBA for the two seasons of 2019-20 and 2020-21, averaging 30.9 PPG on 47.0 FG% with 2.6 3PG. He has struggled with injury in the two seasons since, playing only 90 of 162 games, and his scoring average has fallen into the low-mid 20s. This offseason he was traded out of Washington, and joins Devin Booker and Kevin Durant in Phoenix. Beal projects as the third option, as both a scorer and a playmaker, so may produce lower volumes but likely at higher efficiency due to the open shots his All NBA teammates should create for him.

Carter finished his second full season with the Magic with very similar box score production to his first, finishing fractionally up or down in almost every category. His rebounding had the biggest drop, down almost two per game, perhaps as a nod to the Magic's strong young frontcourt led by Paolo Banchero. Otherwise, Carter was still a solid mid-teens scorer with just under double digit boards and 2.5 combined 3-pointers, steals and blocks to round out his category production.

Nurkic was a top 100 fantasy player early in his career, but his durability has been an issue in recent seasons. The center hasn't played more than 56 games in a season since 2018-19, and hasn't quite been the same player since he broke his leg at the end of that campaign. Three consecutive seasons have gone by without him finishing as a top 100 fantasy player. Last season, Nurkic averaged 13.3 PPG, 9.1 RPG, 1.0 BPG and 3.0 APG in 26.7 MPG. He has been a reliable source of points, rebounds and blocks throughout his career, but now in Phoenix his per game averages will suffer on a team with Kevin Durant, Devin Booker and Bradley Beal.

As Wood bounces around the league, he now finds himself backing up Anthony Davis with the Lakers. Wood's defensive play is questionable at best, but he could be a solid offensive contributor. During the 2022-23 season, he averaged 16.6 PPG, 7.3 RPG, and 1.8 APG in 67 games while shooting 51.5% from the field. With Davis' injury history, Wood could find himself on the streaming radar sooner rather than later.

Smart was traded this offseason as part of the move that sent Kristaps Porzingis to the Celtics, making the Grizzlies his second team in his tenth NBA season. Smart has established an identity as a defensive agitator and tertiary offensive threat, winning the 2021-22 NBA Defensive Player of the Year award and serving as more of an off-ball 3-and-D type than a true point guard with Jayson Tatum and Jaylen Brown handling the ball more. Smart may have the opportunity to be more aggressive on offense for the Grizzlies, particularly during the first 25 games when Ja Morant is suspended. Smart dished a career-best 6.3 APG last season and has upside there, and has even more upside as a scorer, where he has averaged 12.2 PPG in the last three regular seasons but upped that to 15.5 PPG in the last three postseasons.
